                  headcount and response rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Export your list</strong> – Use “Export CSV” to open
                  your guest list in Excel, Google Sheets, or Numbers.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>What does “RSVP” mean?</h2>
              <p>
                The abbreviation <strong>RSVP</strong> comes from the French
                phrase <em>“Répondez, s’il vous plaît”</em>, which literally
                means <strong>“Please respond”</strong>. On an invitation it is
                a polite request to let the host know whether you will attend
                the event or not.
              </p>
              <p>Adding a clear RSVP request and deadline helps you:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Plan the correct number of seats and meals</li>
                <li>Organize seating charts and table assignments</li>
                <li>Control catering and venue costs</li>
                <li>Reduce last‑minute surprises and stress</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Suggested RSVP wording examples</h3>
              <p>
                Here are some simple RSVP phrases you can use on your
                invitations or event website:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <em
                    >“RSVP by 15 June 2025 on our website:
                    calcdomain.com/rsvp”</em
                  >
                </li>
                <li>
                  <em
                    >“Kindly reply by 30 September: Attending / Regretfully
                    decline”</em
                  >
                </li>
                <li>
                  <em
                    >“Please respond by 10 August and let us know any dietary
                    requirements.”</em
                  >
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Best practices for managing RSVPs</h2>
              <h3>1. Decide who is invited (and how many people)</h3>
              <p>
                For each line in the tracker, decide whether it represents a
                single person, a couple, or a whole household. Use the “# of
                people on this RSVP” field to reflect the total number of seats
                you are reserving for them.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Set a realistic RSVP deadline</h3>
              <p>
                For weddings and formal events, set the deadline
                <strong>3–4 weeks before</strong> the event date so you have
                time to confirm:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Catering headcount and menu choices</li>
                <li>Seating chart and table layout</li>
                <li>Printed place cards and programs</li>
                <li>Transport and accommodation if needed</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Track dietary needs and special notes</h3>
              <p>
                Use the “Dietary needs” and “Notes” fields to record allergies,
                vegetarian/vegan requests, children’s menus, or accessibility
                needs. This makes it easy to share a clean list with your
                caterer or venue.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Follow up politely</h3>
              <p>
                A week before the RSVP deadline, filter by
                <strong>No response</strong> and send a friendly reminder by
                email, message, or phone. After the deadline, follow up
                personally with any remaining key guests.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Do I need an account to use this RSVP tracker?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool runs entirely in your browser. You can optionally
                export your data as CSV or JSON to save it or share it with
                someone else.
              </p>

              <h3>Is my guest data stored anywhere?</h3>
              <p>
                The data you enter stays in your browser while the page is open.
                If you want to keep a copy, use the
                <strong>Download JSON</strong> or
                <strong>Export CSV</strong> buttons and save the file to your
                device.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for multiple events?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. You can create a list for one event, download it as JSON,
                then clear the tool and start a new event. When you need to
                revisit an old event, import the saved JSON file.
              </p>
